element_texts.text:
To N Kendall
Marietta Sept 15th 1850
Dear Brother N, 
How much I wish I could be with you at this time! it is a delightful Sabbath morning the sun is shining brightly and scarcely a cloud bedims the face of the heavens; the church bells have just done ringing and all nature animate and inanimate seems quiet everything in keeping with this holy day of rest. I love to have Sabbath come--yes I believe I do more and more this season is such a feast to the soul; it is at this time especially that-- we can lay aside all worldly cares and occupations and turn our thoughts upward to Author of all good. Upon the Sabbath we can see within our own hearts, cultivate and elevate our Heavenly Father now particularly than at other times and how much such communion strengthens us to bear the duties and trials of life. I feel (and I may I even feel thus) that nothing earthly can induce me to give up my religious enjoyments--my hope and faith in immortality and Heaven, it is a happening too pure, too real and lasting to exchange for earths gains and pleasures and if the trials and sorrows which I have had to encounter in my short life have led me to look upon existence in anything of its true light, have weaned my affections from things of earth and taught me to place my trust and confidence in "Him who doeth all things well "glory honor and praise be to Him who hath called me to endure

them, although some of them have been so heart to bear. Sabbath here as you learned is very different from what it is in Kentucky. yet there I had many happy and I trust profitable hours alone in my room, or with you during this day but we could not enjoy the meetings as a general thing could we? Mr Weaver has commenced to day a series of sermons upon the parables of the New Testament, also a series of lectures to the young both of which are to be continued through the Autumn. Notwithstanding society and things of this nature are more congenial to my feelings how than in Mr Washington yet I would rather be there with you, there are many little things in regard to which I should be happier were I with you. I should feel more independent in all respects and should have some one in whom I could place the utmost confidences now I must keep every little thing to myself for I can never open my heart to Brother R -- without reserve and converse with him of all my feelings and whatever concerns me and Brother Jesse you know is young and takes me interest in many things that interests me yet he is improving in a good many things, he goes to church with me, waits upon me in and sits with me, it was hard for him to do it at first but now he seems to like it very much and is ready to go with me anywhere I wish and I think seems more interested in his duties than he has done. I hope and pray he may yet be all we would have him; he is taking lessons in Dearing ; he wished to and so i thought it is best he should, he has a good taste for it I think. Our school is prospering well and generally speaking I am pleased with it, however there are several little things connected with it that do not exactly please me. We remember one hundred and

ten, fifty of whom are girls and there are but five or six that do not study the larger and kind of Arithmetic, Geography and Grammar so that if my patrons are punctual in paying and succeed in pleasing them, I shall do very well in pecuring  point of view. I have almost every kind of study in my department some very good scholars and some poor ones, particularly in Mathematics, the same as I used to have in Kentucky; have seen in French (all beginners, presume shall have more) and four in Drawing and Painting, expect more in this class too. Chemistry I am teaching. Am in school from seven o'clock in the morning with half past five at night or rather in the afternoon where we have supper often which I have been the recitations of one of the young ladies in my room for the sake of having her remain here, she is difficult and has an impediment in her speech and does not like to go into the schoolroom to recite, has been away to a good many schools but would never stay more than a week so we want to keep her, she has been very homesick but think she will stay; she takes a great liking to me so she says-- So you see I am as busy as ever, all the time I have to devote to music, writing etc is a little while in the evening unless I sit up at night which I expect I shall be compelled to do if I attend to thse things for I am determined to get along in school without assistance if possible. Helen has charge of the primary department which consists of twenty eight most of which are boys. There are thirty one in our family; the house is full enough and there is enough to be done I can assure you. Abby has sixteen in Music I think including Helen and myself. the Academy has been papered throughout since you were here and great improvements

The address of this man with whom
Jesse? stopped is E. G. Needdean,
Rossville on Cross Creek, Potowatomie Co, Kansas
I wrote him in order to find out every
particular I could soon after Erasmus
wrote me but have heard nothing from 
my letter; it is six weeks since I wrote
I should think. Abby grandmates? from unclear
High School the last of June and Clara

Kankakee, Ill. May 28th 1871
Dear papa I would like to see you. Very much indeed. We have put tow bouquets of rosys? in the house that wash-woman said that we might have all we wanted of them. I went to church this morning and Ma went too and ma said that

it was a good serman. How is Katie getting a long. I am glad that you are going to bring back Katie for she takes me to such nice rides. I am very well. Good by.
Affectionately, Winnie
